Why is Student the Owning Entity?

In JPA, for every relationship, one side must be the "owning" side and the other is the
"inverse" (or "mappedBy") side.
This is necessary so JPA knows which entity is responsible for managing the relationship
in the database (i.e., which side will update the join table).

In your example:

@Entity
public class Student {
    @ManyToMany
    @JoinTable(
        name = "student_course",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "student_id"),
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "course_id")
    )
    private Set<Course> courses;
}

@Entity
public class Course {
    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "courses")
    private Set<Student> students;
}


Student is the owning side because:
The @JoinTable annotation is on the Student entity.
The Student entity defines how the join table is mapped.
The Course entity uses mappedBy = "courses", which tells JPA that it is the inverse side and
the mapping is controlled by the Student entity.

What does "owning side" mean?
The owning side is the side that controls the relationship and is responsible for updating
the join table.
Only changes made through the owning side are persisted in the join table.
The inverse side is just a mirror; it reflects the relationship but does not control it.

Why do we need an owning side?
To avoid confusion and data inconsistency, JPA requires one side to be responsible for
managing the relationship.
This prevents both entities from trying to update the join table independently, which could
lead to conflicts.

How to decide which is the owning side?
It’s up to you as the developer. Usually, you pick the side that makes the most sense for
your business logic or the side you’ll use most often to manage the relationship.
The owning side is the one without the mappedBy attribute.

Summary Table

Entity	                    Annotation Details	                       Role

Student	                    @ManyToMany + @JoinTable	               Owning side
Course	                    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "courses")	       Inverse side

In short:

The owning side is the one that defines the @JoinTable and manages the join table.
The inverse side uses mappedBy to point to the owning side’s field.
In your example, Student is the owning side because it defines the join table mapping.


What Does "FK to Student" Mean in the Join Table?

When we say "FK to Student" in the context of the join table, we mean:
In the join table (student_course), the column student_id is a foreign key that points to the
primary key (id) in the Student table.
Similarly, course_id is a foreign key in the join table that points to the primary key (id)
in the Course table.
It does NOT mean that the Student entity has a foreign key to the Course table, or vice versa.
The foreign keys exist only in the join table, not in the main entity tables.


Q.What Does mappedBy = "courses" Mean?

In a bidirectional relationship, one side is the "owning side" (which manages the relationship
and the join table), and the other is the "inverse side" (which just reflects the relationship).
The mappedBy attribute tells JPA that this side is not the owner; instead, the relationship is
managed by the field named "courses" in the other entity (Student).

Explanation of a Topic:

Student is the owning side because it defines the @JoinTable and manages the relationship.

The courses field in Student is a set of all the courses a student is enrolled in.
When you add or remove a course from a student’s courses set, JPA updates the join table
accordingly.
Course is the inverse side because it uses mappedBy = "courses".

The students field in Course is a set of all students enrolled in that course.
This field is mapped by the courses field in Student, meaning it reflects the relationship
but does not manage the join table.
JPA knows to look at the courses field in Student to understand and manage the relationship.
